<tr bgcolor="#5B96D8">
<td width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Author</b></font></td><td width="80%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Discussion</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Maxi</b>
<br>17 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>What about artwork??</b>
<br>
<p>Hi everyone,<p></p>It took some time to read every post on the web-site, and it was all very interesting. However, a question is still running: Artwork. What will be the artwork plan of RedBrick. I'm not talking format as I red somewhere that it was to be kept as the Fasa one, which is excellent. I'm wondering about illustrations, drawings, these kinds of things...<br>When I first played Earthdawn, I had (of course) to make a character and I looked at the amazing drawings of Jeff Laubenstein for a long long time, and I have to say that if I like Earthdawn so much now is on one part because of him. He, I think, had the best style to illustrate the complexity of Barsaive (and more..) as it is described in the texts of the numerous sourcebooks. I'm not saying that other artworks were not good (well, at least not all of them), but Jeff Laubenstein was just fitting perfectly with this ED world. <p></p>Artwork makes a huge difference, and it can bring the status of a game from good to very good. It's not everything, ok, but it plays a role when a new gamer is looking for a game. In the shop, he (or she) won't have time to read the 200 pages of a game to get the picture, but he'll have a browse and check the artwork. If it's good, well, he might buy the game...So it's also a commercial attribute. For all the old fans of ED, it might be secondary; for example, the GM of our group bought the Living Room game line even if he thought that the artwork was, to be polite, not the best he've seen. But someone who thinks about buying ED 2nd edition will think twice when looking at some of the artwork. I don't blame LRG for that as I guess (I don't know the RPG business) that it's quite complicated to find people to do excellent artwork for cheap...<br>So, I have concerns about the artwork plan of RedBrick. I would like to know more about it. Artists maybe? Have you hired J. Laubenstein maybe? :)<p></p>Maxi</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>crackhead don</b>
<br>5 December 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>What about artwork??</b>
<br>
<p>you know, this is old and dead, but i just found this place and am seriously stoked about the interest in 1st ed earthdawn. my girlfriend has recently rekindled my interest in finishing my long ago started fiction and now that i am here i might try just that extra bit more.<p></p>anyway, i was really posting to agree with maxi about laubenstein's work for earthdawn. he's not too fitting with shadowrun and i know others don't like his stuff, but he was the very essence of earthdawn to me. if his work came with the new products, i might buy it for that alone.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
 
